{{context|date=August 2012}}

'''Open lung ventilation''' is a strategy that is utilized by several [[modes of mechanical ventilation]] to combine low tidal volume and applied [[Positive end-expiratory pressure|PEEP]] to maximize recruitment of alveoli.  The low [[tidal volume]] aims to minimize alveolar overdistention and the PEEP minimizes cyclic atelectasis.  Working in tandem the effects from both decrease the risk of [[ventilator-associated lung injury]].

==Benefit==
Some clinical trials indicate that open lung ventilation may improve mortality, other clinically important outcomes, and oxygenation.<ref name="pmid9449727">{{cite journal| author=Amato MB, Barbas CS, Medeiros DM, Magaldi RB, Schettino GP, Lorenzi-Filho G et al.| title=Effect of a protective-ventilation strategy on mortality in the acute respiratory distress syndrome. | journal=N Engl J Med | year= 1998 | volume= 338 | issue= 6 | pages= 347–54 | pmid=9449727 | doi=10.1056/NEJM199802053380602 | pmc= | url= }}</ref><ref name="pmid16557151">{{cite journal| author=Villar J, Kacmarek RM, Pérez-Méndez L, Aguirre-Jaime A| title=A high positive end-expiratory pressure, low tidal volume ventilatory strategy improves outcome in persistent acute respiratory distress syndrome: a randomized, controlled trial. | journal=Crit Care Med | year= 2006 | volume= 34 | issue= 5 | pages= 1311–8 | pmid=16557151 | doi=10.1097/01.CCM.0000215598.84885.01 | pmc= | url= }}</ref>

==Dangers==
Open lung ventilation is generally well tolerated.<ref name="pmid16557151"/>

==Application==
A universally accepted protocol for open lung ventilation has not been established.<ref name="pmid16557151"/>

